{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fa077b59-fdf4-4bcb-b0f2-e3aca48253b9","content":"I don't see the project at that path in this environment, but here's how to configure it.\n\nCreate `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace root:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`command`/`args`** — runs `dotnet run --project <path>` to start your server.\n- If you publish a self-contained binary instead, point `command` directly at the executable.\n- Make sure your server uses **stdio transport** (not HTTP/SSE) — this is the standard for MCP in VS Code agent mode.\n\nAfter saving, VS Code will discover the server automatically when you use Copilot in agent mode.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e4726e28-5c19-4227-b64f-0b45507d1a50","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project doesn't exist at that path, but the user said they built it there. Regardless, I can still answer their question about how to configure `mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using `dotnet run` as the stdio transport.","outputTokens":322,"requestId":"5C37:3D597:1CD5044:1FF129F:69FA933A"},"id":"24980655-f294-4b86-b2d3-de2d92cb0258","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:03:00.546Z","parentId":"daf5c73e-782c-42ea-bdb3-26d0f9226e23"}
